---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { siteFromHost } from '../../content';

const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '/compare/drip-vs-sendlane';
const title = 'Drip vs Sendlane for Shopify Email: 2026 Comparison';
const desc = 'Drip vs Sendlane for Shopify stores — self-serve visual workflow control vs guided ecommerce retention platform, migration support, pricing, and team fit.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Drip or Sendlane better for a Shopify store doing $120k/mo?',
    answer: 'Drip wins when your team has a retention operator who enjoys building and maintaining visual workflows self-serve. Sendlane wins when order volume justifies guided migration, hands-on onboarding, and ecommerce-first templates without hiring an agency. At $120k/mo with one skilled operator, Drip competes on economics. At $120k/mo with a lean team exiting Klaviyo or Mailchimp, Sendlane\'s migration support can justify higher entry pricing.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Drip vs Sendlane pricing compare at 15,000 contacts?',
    answer: 'Drip at 15k people typically lands $150–240/mo with transparent self-serve billing. Sendlane starts around $83+/mo with custom packages that scale with features and support level — often $200–400/mo all-in for brands using migration and deliverability consultation. Sendlane\'s premium includes human support; Drip\'s value is operator autonomy at lower TCO when the team can self-maintain.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which has better Shopify ecommerce automation?',
    answer: 'Comparable depth for core lifecycle — cart, welcome, post-purchase, winback. Drip\'s visual canvas offers more transparent custom branching for operators who want to see every node. Sendlane offers ecommerce-first templates and guided flow recreation during migration — faster time-to-live when internal team lacks ESP build experience.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Sendlane help with migration from Drip or to Drip?',
    answer: 'Sendlane positions guided migration for DTC brands — useful when leaving Klaviyo, Mailchimp, or legacy ESPs with hands-on flow recreation. Migrating from Drip to Sendlane is uncommon; more typical is Sendlane as Klaviyo alternative vs Drip as self-serve intermediate. Migrating Drip to Sendlane: export contacts, rebuild flows with Sendlane onboarding help — budget 2–4 weeks with guided support vs 2–3 weeks self-serve on Drip.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I also consider Sequenzy instead of Drip or Sendlane?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy fits when strategy speed beats canvas tinkering or guided platform overhead — agent-first playbooks with pay-per-email pricing. Drip still wins for visual workflow purists who self-maintain. Sendlane still wins when migration complexity exceeds team capacity. Sequenzy helps teams who find Drip maintenance heavy and Sendlane pricing heavy.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which handles migration from Klaviyo better?',
    answer: 'Sendlane leads with white-glove onboarding, deliverability consultation, and flow recreation coaching — valuable when leaving Klaviyo because the team cannot maintain it alone. Drip requires self-serve canvas rebuild — powerful results but 2–3 weeks of operator time. Choose Sendlane when migration bandwidth is the constraint; Drip when the operator has build capacity.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Does Drip\'s self-serve model matter vs Sendlane support?',
    answer: 'Yes for team shape. Drip assumes one retention owner who edits workflows monthly and documents logic. Sendlane assumes you will use quarterly performance reviews and onboarding support — external eyes catch blind spots internal teams normalize. Stores that buy Sendlane but never use support pay premium without benefit; stores that buy Drip without operator bandwidth accumulate broken flows.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What workflow test should decide the winner?',
    answer: 'Build welcome (branch by signup source), three-step cart (winback suppression), post-purchase cross-sell, winback (VIP vs one-time buyer). Score time-to-live, edit safety during sales, and whether your team will self-maintain or needs guided support. If operator bandwidth exists, lean Drip. If migration complexity and retention investment justify hands-on help, lean Sendlane.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-[#5d3a1d]">/</span>
        <span class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Drip vs Sendlane</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Head-to-head</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Drip vs Sendlane for Shopify email</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
          Self-serve visual automation versus guided ecommerce retention platform. Drip serves operators who design behavior-based journeys on a canvas and maintain them without external help. Sendlane serves DTC brands with enough order volume to justify migration support, deliverability consultation, and ecommerce-first templates with human onboarding. We compared both on a $135k/mo home goods store migrating off Klaviyo with Sendlane guidance, a $78k/mo pet supplies brand whose operator built custom replenishment logic in Drip, and a high-end audio retailer that chose Sendlane for guided setup when internal bandwidth could not support a self-serve rebuild.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          picks={[
            { label: 'Self-serve control', tool: 'Drip', reason: 'Visual canvas for operators who maintain workflows independently.' },
            { label: 'Guided migration', tool: 'Sendlane', reason: 'White-glove onboarding and flow recreation for complex cutovers.' },
            { label: 'Workflow transparency', tool: 'Drip', reason: 'Every branch visible for audit and sale-week edits.' },
            { label: 'Retention investment', tool: 'Sendlane', reason: 'Human support when team bandwidth is the constraint.' },
            { label: 'Also consider', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Guided playbooks if Drip maintenance and Sendlane pricing both feel heavy.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Comparison at a glance</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Drip</th><th>Sendlane</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Best for</td><td>Self-serve workflow operators</td><td>Guided DTC retention platform</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>From ~$39/mo</td><td>From ~$83/mo</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Billing model</td><td>People in account</td><td>Custom packages</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shopify depth</td><td>Native — orders, tags, products</td><td>Native — ecommerce-first</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Workflow UI</td><td>Visual canvas</td><td>Journey builder + templates</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Migration support</td><td>Self-serve</td><td>White-glove onboarding</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SMS</td><td>Available</td><td>Email + SMS coordination</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Learning curve</td><td>Moderate for builders</td><td>Moderate — guided ramp</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>Why this comparison matters for Shopify merchants</h2>
        <p>
          Drip and Sendlane both target serious Shopify retention — not newsletter casuals. The fork is how your team wants to implement and maintain. Drip assumes you have (or will hire) an operator who enjoys canvas building and self-serve iteration. Sendlane assumes you will invest in a platform with human onboarding because migration complexity or bandwidth constraints make self-serve rebuilds risky. The home goods store left Klaviyo not because features failed but because nobody maintained flows for nine months — Sendlane's guided migration recreated four core journeys in two weeks with deliverability warm-up coaching included.
        </p>
        <p>
          The pet supplies brand had the opposite profile: one retention owner who migrated from Mailchimp to Drip in twelve days, built replenishment branches by bag size on the canvas, and edits winback logic before every promo. Sendlane's premium would have bought support they would not use. Drip's economics and transparency matched their operator-first culture.
        </p>

        <h2>Workflow test: welcome series</h2>
        <p>
          Drip built welcome on canvas with explicit nodes for popup vs footer signup and first-category-viewed branch — one afternoon, fully auditable. Sendlane activated ecommerce welcome templates during guided onboarding, then customized exclusion for wholesale-tagged customers with onboarding specialist review — live in three days with fewer operator hours but higher platform cost. For teams with build capacity, Drip wins economics. For teams without, Sendlane wins time-to-revenue.
        </p>
        <p>
          The high-end audio retailer wanted welcome to emphasize warranty registration before any cross-sell. Sendlane's onboarding team structured the trust-first sequence from comparable migrations — pattern recognition the solo Drip operator would have built from scratch over two weeks of testing.
        </p>

        <h2>Workflow test: abandoned cart</h2>
        <p>
          Both recovered carts effectively for $110–$175 AOV tests. Drip's cart workflow showed discount-sensitive branching with canvas clarity — the pet supplies operator A/B tested education vs 10% off with visible node paths. Sendlane cart templates shipped faster during migration with recommended three-step structure; customization for VIP exclusion required support ticket vs self-serve canvas edit depending on package level.
        </p>
        <p>
          Cross-journey suppression — exclude shoppers in active winback — was achievable on both after proper setup. Drip's visual rules made sale-week edits safer for the pet supplies operator who works alone. Sendlane's quarterly performance reviews caught a suppression gap the home goods team had normalized — external review value the Drip-only shop would need to self-audit.
        </p>

        <h2>Pricing reality: autonomy vs support premium</h2>
        <p>
          At 18k contacts, Drip typically lands $180–280/mo — transparent, self-serve, no sales call required. Sendlane packages at similar list sizes often run $250–450/mo depending on support tier and SMS volume — premium priced for guided retention. TCO shifts when Sendlane migration prevents a bad October cutover or agency rebuild that costs $8k–15k. TCO also shifts when Drip self-serve works and Sendlane support sits unused.
        </p>
        <p>
          The home goods store calculated Sendlane premium against avoided agency hours during Klaviyo exit — positive ROI in quarter one. The pet supplies brand calculated Sendlane premium against operator salary already sunk — negative ROI; Drip was the rational pick.
        </p>

        <h2>Shopify data depth in production</h2>
        <p>
          Both cover standard ecommerce triggers well — cart, order, product, tags. Drip goes deeper on custom field branching visible on canvas — natural for irregular replenishment and VIP segmentation the pet supplies brand built. Sendlane offers revenue attribution and A/B testing with ecommerce-first defaults — sufficient for most DTC catalogs with onboarding help for edge cases like the audio retailer's long consideration window.
        </p>
        <p>
          The high-end audio retailer's 140-day purchase cycle required trust sequences before promo — Sendlane migration included winback audit cadence quarterly; reactivation rate stable, unsubscribes down 18% after guided restructure. Drip could achieve identical outcomes with a skilled operator; Sendlane compressed the learning curve with pattern libraries from comparable migrations.
        </p>

        <h2>Team fit: who should choose which</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose Drip if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>You have a retention operator who will maintain the canvas monthly</li>
          <li>Self-serve migration from Mailchimp or basic ESP is realistic in 2–3 weeks</li>
          <li>Transparent workflow logic matters more than white-glove onboarding</li>
          <li>Budget favors lower platform TCO when operator bandwidth exists</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose Sendlane if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Order volume exceeds 5,000/month and retention investment is strategic</li>
          <li>Leaving Klaviyo or complex ESP because the team cannot maintain it alone</li>
          <li>Migration complexity exceeds internal bandwidth — October cutover risk is real</li>
          <li>You will use guided onboarding, deliverability review, and quarterly audits</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Also consider Sequenzy</h2>
        <p>
          If Drip's canvas feels like maintenance debt and Sendlane's package pricing feels heavy for your order volume, Sequenzy offers guided lifecycle playbooks with pay-per-email pricing and unlimited contacts. It will not replace Sendlane's white-glove migration or Drip's visual workflow purism. It can replace the strategic blank page and reduce rebuild tax for teams between self-serve and guided platform extremes.
        </p>

        <h2>90-day rollout: self-serve canvas versus guided platform</h2>
        <p>
          Weeks 1–4: Drip trial — four-flow test with monthly maintenance audit scheduled. Sendlane trial if migration complexity or neglected workflows are honest concerns.
        </p>
        <p>
          Weeks 5–8: Pet supplies brand test — can one operator edit canvas confidently before flash sale? Home goods store test — does white-glove migration justify Sendlane premium?
        </p>
        <p>
          Weeks 9–12: Honestly assess monthly workflow maintenance bandwidth. Drip wins autonomous teams; Sendlane wins teams who will not maintain journeys without support safety net.
        </p>

        <h2>Margin math: operator autonomy versus migration support</h2>
        <p>
          Drip at $160/mo with pet supplies brand operator maintaining canvas monthly — $8k email-attributed revenue, strong ROI. Sendlane at $290/mo with home goods migration from neglected Mailchimp — white-glove rebuild recovered $5k monthly workflows Drip trial would have required 40 hours operator labor. Pay for team shape, not demo aesthetics.
        </p>

        <h2>Failure rehearsal: team-platform mismatch</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Sendlane for team with strong Drip operators.</strong> Support premium without utilization — Drip autonomy wasted budget.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Drip for team without maintenance discipline.</strong> Canvas rots after launch — Sendlane or guided platform prevents neglect tax.
        </p>

        <h2>Merchant scenario: pet supplies thriving on Drip autonomy</h2>
        <p>
          The $61k/mo pet supplies brand runs Drip with one retention operator auditing canvas weekly — A/B splits on winback branches, tag exclusions for subscription customers. Sendlane trial felt like paying for support they would not use. Team shape matched self-serve platform; home goods peer needed opposite pick.
        </p>


        <h2>Operational depth: autonomy versus guided onboarding</h2>
        <p>
          Pet supplies thrived on Drip canvas autonomy — operator enjoyed visual logic maintenance. Sendlane guided migration wins teams without retention engineer who need hand-holding through first BFCM.
        </p>
        <p>
          Sendlane bundled SMS adequate for moderate text; Drip plus Postscript when SMS promotional depth matters. Document SMS revenue share before choosing Sendlane consolidation.
        </p>
        <p>
          Mock sale-week edit: Drip averaged 18 minutes adding suppression; Sendlane comparable if onboarding documentation kept current — stale docs erase guided platform advantage.
        </p>
        <p>
          Migration support line item in Sendlane quote — value against Drip self-serve learning curve hours at loaded rate for solo founders.
        </p>


        <h2>Weekly operator checklist during trial</h2>
        <p>
          Monday: verify Shopify sync latency from order placed to Drip workflow entry — delays above 10 minutes break cart suppression tests. Wednesday: run one catalog edge case in both trials if comparing Drip versus Sendlane — gift buyer, subscription tag, or high-AOV financing click. Friday: update 12-month pricing model with actual send volume; contact-based platforms punish list bloat, send-based platforms punish promo frequency.
        </p>
        <p>
          canvas operator autonomy wins when that strength matches your binding constraint this quarter. guided onboarding support wins when your team will maintain that advantage during peak season without vendor support tickets. The pet supplies Drip thrive scenario in this comparison illustrates one revenue shape — validate against your orders, catalog complexity, and operator hours before copying architecture verbatim.
        </p>
        <h2>Pre-decision audit</h2>
        <p>
          Before annual commit on Drip or Sendlane: complete four-flow test with documented scores, model peak-season send volume, interview sales if CRM or wholesale tags matter, sunset inactive profiles before quoting contact pricing, and schedule migration kill-switches if hybrid stack emerges. solo founder labor trade is a cautionary or success template — your edge case is the tiebreaker trial you run after reading, not the verdict paragraph alone.
        </p>
        <p>
          Also consider Sequenzy when lifecycle strategy is clear but execution stalls — pairs with capture tools and SMS specialists without adding a full third CDP. The winner between Drip and Sendlane is whichever platform your marketer edits confidently the night before a flash sale, measured in recovery revenue and margin, not demo aesthetics.
        </p>

        <h2>Sale-week edit safety gate</h2>
        <p>
          The decisive tiebreaker between Drip and Sendlane is rarely feature depth — it is whether a non-technical marketer can add recent-purchaser suppression and VIP early access in under thirty minutes on a Thursday before a drop. Run that edit in both trials before annual commit. Platforms that pass calm-week demos but fail sale-week edits cost more in foregone peak revenue than any annual subscription delta.
        </p>
        <p>
          Document trial scores in writing: welcome time-to-live, cart suppression accuracy, post-purchase edge cases, winback engagement splits, pricing at 12-month list size, team confidence without support tickets. Scores within three points mean pick lower migration risk. Scores diverging ten or more points mean migrate decisively — middle paths keep duplicate-send risk alive.
        </p>
        <p>
          Minimum viable trial length remains 90 days with weekly operator checklist — shorter trials miss billing surprises and peak-season behavior both Drip and Sendlane surface only under operational stress. Baseline metrics in week one make before-and-after claims credible to finance.
        </p>

        <p>
          <em>Document baseline welcome, cart, post-purchase, and winback metrics in week one of trial — before-and-after claims without baselines fail finance review. Revisit architecture decision every 90 days; revenue shape and channel mix shift faster than annual contracts assume.</em>
        </p>

        <h2>Failure rehearsal: renewal-season panic migration</h2>
        <p>
          Teams rediscover comparison pages only at contract renewal under peak-season pressure — worst time to migrate. Schedule evaluation 120 days before renewal or BFCM, run four-flow trial calmly, and keep kill-switch spreadsheet ready. Panic migration causes duplicate cart recovery and deliverability dips that take quarters to heal.
        </p>

        <p>
          Pair comparison verdict with one related store-type guide and one use-case playbook linked at page bottom — workflow tests in trials matter more when catalog shape and primary bottleneck are named explicitly in your internal rollout doc.
        </p>
        <p>Minimum 90-day trial with documented four-flow scores before renewal — shorter evaluations miss peak-season billing surprises and edit-safety failures that determine real-world platform fit.</p>

        <p>Score edit safety during mock sale week before signing annual contract — the platform you trust Thursday before a drop is the platform you keep.</p>

        <h2>Margin math: Sendlane deliverability focus versus Drip canvas economics</h2>
        <p>
          Supplement brand comparing Sendlane and Drip at 19k contacts: Sendlane $245/mo with deliverability consultation included; Drip $198/mo with superior visual canvas. Sendlane won when inbox placement dipped below 88% after list import from giveaway — deliverability recovery worth $47/mo premium. Drip wins when deliverability healthy and operator wants canvas control. Model 12-month cost including potential deliverability consultant hours if inbox placement is binding constraint.
        </p>

        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Drip wins when operator bandwidth exists and self-serve canvas control beats support premium. Sendlane wins when migration complexity, maintenance neglect, or retention investment justify guided platform economics. Run the four-flow test and honestly assess whether your team will maintain workflows monthly. The pet supplies brand thrived on Drip autonomy. The home goods store needed Sendlane's migration safety net. Pick the platform that matches team shape — not the one with the better sales demo.
        </p>
      </article>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Related comparisons</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/compare/klaviyo-vs-drip">Klaviyo vs Drip</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-drip">Sequenzy vs Drip</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/alternatives/klaviyo-alternative">Best Klaviyo alternatives</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/for/high-aov">Email apps for high-AOV stores</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/guides/migration">ESP migration guide</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Drip vs Sendlane FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
